<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n10012i"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n10" href="#n10012i">N10 (VI.B.16)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n10all.htm#n10012i"> 12(i)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Easterner</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">The records are silent on this point <font color="green">[the Christianisation of the Vikings in Ireland]</font> with regard to Olaf the White, although he was related by marriage to Ketill Flatnose, a famous chief in the Hebrides, all of whose family, with the exception of his son <mark>Bj&ouml;rn the Easterner</mark>, adopted Christianity. Olaf&apos;s wife, Authr <font color="green">[Ota]</font>, daughter of Ketill, was one of the most zealous of these early Norse converts: &ldquo;She used to pray at Crossknolls, where she had crosses erected, because she was baptised, and was a good Christian&rdquo;. <small> A. WALSH, <a name="AWSR" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#AWSR"><cite title="source">Scandinavian Relations with Ireland During the Viking Period</cite></a> (1922) 48</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c06145a" href="c6all.htm#c06145a">VI.C.06:145(a)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
